title: For Sale:  WWI Imperial Luger c.1915
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent:
This is an almost completely matching, 1915 Dated, DWM (Deutsche Waffen und Munitions Fabriken) WWI Imperial Luger. It is chambered for 9mm and has a standard 4" (100mm) barrel, fixed sights and walnut grips. The serial number appears on the front of the frame, on the left side of the receiver, on the side plate sear and trigger. The 1914 Model Luger is characterized by the short frame, the rear "V" cut fixed and front dovetailed sight, and the frame with the stock lug. It was produced from 1914 until 1918 for the German Military. 

The right side of the receiver displays all the Imperial Army acceptance stamps. Original grips are finely cut diamond shaped checkering made from walnut or in some cases beech wood. These grips are serial numbered to the gun. The inside of the gun is clean and well cared for. The exterior shows honest wear on the muzzle, barrel and high points on the sides. The barrel is shiny and shows distinct lands and grooves. This Luger shows characteristic holster wear on the side plate and front exposed edges of the rails and end of the barrel. I would rate it about 80% original finish. 

The Luger is accompanied by three magazines and a WWII issue holster with German military markings. With the magazines and about a $250 holster, this gun is priced reasonably.

title: For Sale:  Custom Tactical Long Range “Sniper” Rifle
postcontent:
Remington Model 700 SPS Varmint rifle #84218, 26” heavy barrel, in .308 Win. Pillar bedded in stock and barrel is fully floated. (Includes factory paperwork)

Pacific Tool & Gauge (PTG) SA Stainless Steel Fluted Firing Pin Assembly with upgraded spring 

HS Precision A5 stock #PST025, Kevlar/Graphite composite, pillar bedded, fully adjustable cheek rest and length of pull (LOP), improved palm swell, in Black with Olive web

HS Precision built-in Adjustable Grip Stand (optional rear monopod)

Timney Rem 700 40x Trigger, adjustable 1.5 to 4 lb (originally set at 2.5)

Wyatt’s Outdoor M700 DETMAG aluminum Detachable Bottom Metal (DBM) kit, with one 5 round magazine, and one extra 5 round magazine

Harris Ultralight Series “S” class 6 x 9 Bipod, Model “BR” (HBRS) with Harris “Pod-Loc” lever

Badger Ordnance Rem SA aluminum scope rail with built-in 20 MOA (receiver drilled and tapped with proper 8-40 screws)

Badger Ordnance Tactical Bolt Knob

Millett LRS-1 6 x 25 Illuminated Scope #81007 with HUGE 56mm objective/35mm tube, glass-etched reticule, variable objective (parallax), tactical knobs (.1 Mil click), sun shade, and flip-up caps.

Counter Sniper 35mm railed scope rings #DOH367 (spare smooth rings included)

Yankee Hill Machine Phantom 7.62 QD Brake #YHM-3302-MB-24A (not installed)

Plano Gun Guard 52” Case (just something to put it in)

Much of the existing work on this weapon was performed by Red Hawk Rifles in Colorado. Like new except for a very few “handling” marks, with less than 100 rounds through it. Although there is nothing wrong with the factory barrel, I never quite decided whether I might switch to an aftermarket barrel, maybe shorten the existing one or just thread it, so the brake was never installed (but it’s included if you want it). The rings came out a bit high for my taste (the cheek adjustment ensures its no functional issue), but since I never absolutely decided on a barrel profile, I never finalized my mount choice (McCann, Precision Reflex etc), so the rings had to wait. I was going to turn the whole thing over to Score High Gunsmithing in Albuquerque for their “accurizing” once I made all my final component decisions. This was intended for tactical and long range applications, maybe competition or critter destruction “from one zip code over”, but I don’t think I’d actually want to carry her very far for hunting; she’s sexy beast, but she is a big girl.

Overall this is a VERY sweet and accurate rifle; it might run $4000-$5000 to have it built for you, it has nearly $3500 in components alone (not including locating, ordering, shipping, and installation). I checked on manufacturers to get those prices, but there are lots of sites out there, so you should check for yourself. You might “find a deal” on some of them for reference. 

I’m asking $2500 for everything and I may consider removing/not including certain components (scope or bipod etc) depending on the deal if you want. I’m not in a rush, only selling because other projects are waiting. Cash talks, low-ballers will be ignored.

Shipping to an FFL is possible but is not included free.

PARTIAL TRADES CONSIDERED.

Pictures are old and fuzzy and don’t even come close so call/text or email to see in person. Five-oh-five 712 five-one-three-four

Thanks!
